By design, SVE consists of alignment, realignment and the ensemble of state-of-the-art SV-calling algorithms by default. They are BreakDancer, BreakSeq, cnMOPS, CNVnator, DELLY, Hydra and LUMPY. FusorSV is also embedded that is a data mining approach to assess performance and merge callsets from an ensemble of SV-calling algorithms.

name: ORCA
description:
Genomics Research Container Architecture - 
ORCA is a platform for bioinformatics analysis. It is suited for those wishing to conduct self-serve analysis using their own existing data. Hundreds of bioinformatics tools from Homebrew-Science are installed in the ORCA Docker image using Linuxbrew.

To quickly get up and running with ORCA, run...

docker run -it bcgsc/orca
See versions.tsv for the complete list of installed tools, and see the ORCA web site for more information. The changes in formulae versions from the previous release of ORCA are listed at https://bcgsc.github.io/orca/

Configurig ORCA for local usage is provided here. Configuring ORCA for use on a multi-user system is described for Hackseq2017 and MICB405.

overview: Ancestry pipeline to estimate the geographic regions where your ancestors lived some indeterminate time in the past. The Nextflow pipeline estimates ancestry/admixture proportions of 23andMe files using the tools fastNGSadmix & iAdmix. The output is a CSV file containing the estimated ancestry proportions.

name: Polygenic Risk Scores
description: Calculate genetic risk score for any given phenotype/trait
overview: Calculate Polygenic Risk Scores (PRS) for any given phenotype/trait, using PRSice (Choi and O'Reilly, 2019) The web interface currently offers the minimum number of required parameters for this pipeline for simplicity and ease. However, the pipeline was built with flexibility in mind and supports a wide array of parameters which can be found in the documentation and set when using the API. The pipeline takes a base or discovery set produced as the output of a previous GWAS analysis. The PRS generated from that base data are then applied to a different dataset. The outputs include a test summary file containing 11 columns on Phenotype, Set, Threshold, PRS.R2, Full.R2, Null.R2, Prevalence, Coefficient, P, Num_SNP, Empirical-P. As well as various plots and a summary report to show the results of the polygenic risk scores.

The application provides fast discovery of antimicrobial patterns in proteins that can be used to develop new peptide-based drugs against pathogens.

overview: Performs a PheWAS analysis & generates a Manhattan plot using the PheWAS R package. The pipeline takes two CSV files as input, one for the genotype data and one for the phenotypic data (for more information see the documentation). Accepted phenotypic codes include both International Classification of Disease v9 (ICD9) and Disease Ontology (DO) codes. The output of the pipeline includes a Manhattan plot summarising the PheWAS analysis, PLINK binary files containing the genotype information for all individuals and the raw data for further downstream analyses.

name: HotNet2
description: HotNet2, an algorithm for finding significantly altered subnetworks in a large gene interaction network by Medley Genomics
overview:
HotNet2, an algorithm for finding significantly altered subnetworks in a large gene interaction network by Medley Genomics. The pipeline utilises a protein-protein interaction network and the alteration or "heat" scores on the genes of the network, where the heat scores reflect the recurrence or significance of alterations in each gene. Medley Genomics Inc.:
The heterogeneity of patient disease remains a significant challenge in understanding how best to discover and develop new therapies which offer hope of lasting cures for patients. With ever increasing big data derived from diverse biological measurements, new solutions are necessary to decipher complex pathways including novel gene-gene and protein-protein interactions. Medley Genomics Inc. has developed a suite of computational and algorithmic solutions to enable more comprehensive understanding of disease biology and to better define disease sub-populations using novel solutions. HotNet2 software provides a network tool to allow analysis of high-dimensional omics data by leveraging biological interaction networks. HotNet2 can has been used for a wide range of applications, such as the use of protein-protein interaction networks to analyse gene expression data, to prioritise germline variants and to identify somatic driver mutations in cancer. In these and other applications, the underlying computational problem is to identify altered subnetworks containing genes that are both highly altered in an omics dataset and are topologically close (e.g. connected) on an interaction network. With HotNet2, we provide an important solution for examining heterogeneity of disease across patient cohorts and has the ability to utilize multiple difference omics data sets. While we have focused early efforts on applying this approach to oncology data sets, our customers have extended the use of HotNet2 to a variety of complex diseases to reveal the underlying heterogeneity of patient populations, to detect possible patient sub-groups and to elucidate novel targets and pathways. Based on innovative algorithms and computational approaches developed by Medley Genomics co-founder, Dr Ben Raphael, and his research group during his tenure at Brown University and now at Princeton University, Medley Genomics has exclusive commercial licenses for distribution of innovative statistical solutions for understanding the underlying biology of human disease. HotNet2 is now offered in partnership with Lifebit with a shared goal of enabling researchers to seamlessly and at scale execute their analyses on the Lifebit Deploit platform. Reference: Leiserson MD, Vandin F, Wu HT, Dobson JR, Eldridge JV, Thomas JL, Papoutsaki A, Kim Y, Niu B, McLellan M, Lawrence MS, Gonzalez-Perez A, Tamborero D, Cheng Y, Ryslik GA, Lopez-Bigas N, Getz G, Ding L, Raphael BJ (2015) Pan-cancer network analysis identifies combinations of rare somatic mutations across pathways and protein complexes. Nat Genet. 47(2):106-14."

name: Dragen
description: Illumina's Dragen pipeline for mapping & germline variant calling.
overview: Illumina's Dragen pipeline for mapping & germline variant calling. The pipeline takes paired-end gzipped FASTQ as input and outputs a gzipped VCF file & interactive MultiQC report. Reference genomes for GRCh37 & GRCh38 are already provided. Illumina: DRAGEN performs decompression, mapping, aligning, sorting, and optional duplicate marking and feeds directly into the variant caller to produce a VCF file. In this mode, DRAGEN uses parallel stages throughout the pipeline to drastically reduce the overall run time.

name: Dragen Somatic
description: Illumina's Dragen pipeline for mapping & somatic variant calling.
overview: Illumina's Dragen pipeline for mapping & somatic variant calling. The pipeline runs Dragen in tumor-normal mode using a Nextflow wrapper script so that you just need to supply a CSV containing the path to your input files (see [gitbook documentation](https://lifebit.gitbook.io/deploit/pipelines-documentations-and-examples-1/modules/dragen-somatic)). The pipeline produces output VCF files & a MultiQC report. Illumina: The DRAGEN Somatic Pipeline allows ultrarapid analysis of NGS data to identify cancer-associated mutations. DRAGEN calls SNVs and indels from both matched tumor-normal pairs and tumor-only samples. For the tumor-normal pipeline, both samples are analyzed jointly such that germline variants are excluded, generating an output specific to tumor mutations.

name: Dragen CNV
description: Illumina's Dragen pipeline for mapping & copy number variant analysis.
overview: Illumina's Dragen pipeline for mapping & copy number variant analysis. The pipeline uses a Nextflow wrapper script so that you just need to supply the paired-end reads files as gzipped FASTQ files. The pipeline produces output VCF files & a MultiQC report. Pre-indexed GRCh37 and GRCh38 reference genomes are provided. Illumina: The DRAGEN CNV pipeline is capable of calling copy number variant events using next generation sequencing (NGS) data. The pipeline supports multiple applications in a single interface via the DRAGEN Host Software. This includes processing of whole genome sequencing data and whole exome sequencing data for germline analysis. The DRAGEN CNV pipeline supports two normalization modes of operation. The two modes apply different normalisation techniques to handle biases which differ based on the application, for example, WGS versus WES.

name: Dragen Mapping
description: Illumina's Dragen pipeline for mapping only.
overview: Illumina's Dragen pipeline for mapping only. Ultrafast mapping-only pipeline to run Illumina's hardware-accelerated Dragen on FPGA instances. The pipeline takes paired-end gzipped FASTQ from the input folder and maps them to the selected reference genome. Currently, available reference genomes are GRCh37 & GRCh38. The output Dragen produces is an aligned and sorted BAM.
